Establishing the distribution of three agar-producing seaweed species in relation to existing Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) in South Africa

Lilith Diener

2025-03-01

To assess whether new Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) should be established or existing ones expanded for the conservation of South Africa’s main agar-producing seaweed species, I outline my step-by-step workflow below.

Firstly, I install and load all necessary packages.

Here, I generate some plots to get an overview of the MPA data, I then reduce it to show only the relevant column (MPA names) and create an additional plot using tidyverse, which also creates a legend. In this last plot the map is squashed, but I will fix this in the next step.

# Plot all (all columns, all of SA)
plot(mpa)
## Warning: plotting the first 9 out of 11 attributes; use max.plot = 11 to plot
## all

Figure 1: Plots of the properties of each attribute in the MPA attribute table.

# Plot only column 2 from attribute table, all of SA
 plot(mpa[2])

Figure 2: Map of South African Marine Protected Areas by name.

# Plot using tidyverse
ggplot() + geom_sf(data=mpa, aes(fill = `CUR_NME`))

Figure 3: Map of South African Marine Protected Areas with legend.

To avoid squashing the map, I crop it to the section I want to show. I set the bounding box to show the Cape Peninsula, and extend west and north to include Robben Island, and east and south to include more of False Bay.

 # Define bounding box size
xmin <- 18.0   # Extend west to include Robben Island
xmax <- 19.2   # Extend east to include parts of False Bay
ymin <- -34.6  # Extend south to cover more of False Bay
ymax <- -33.7  # Extend north to include Robben Island

I create a bounding box with the same CRS as my MPA data, crop it to the Cape Peninsula region and surrounding areas, and plot this.

# Create a bounding box with the same CRS as the MPA data
cape_bbox <- st_bbox(c(xmin = xmin, xmax = xmax, ymin = ymin, ymax = ymax), crs = st_crs(mpa))
 
# Crop the MPA data to the chosen region
mpa_cape <- st_crop(mpa, cape_bbox)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
## all geometries
# Plot only cropped section of Cape Peninsula
plot(st_geometry(mpa_cape), col = 'lightblue', main = "Marine Protected Areas")

Figure 4: Map of South African MPAs in the Cape Peninsula region, Robben Island and False Bay.

I create a plot using ggplot2 showing the four MPAs included in my cropped section in different colours. For this to work, I first convert my MPA data to a data frame.

# Convert MPA data to a data frame for ggplot2
mpa_cape$MPA_NAME <- as.factor(mpa_cape$CUR_NME)  # Convert MPAs to factor values

# Plot colour-coded MPAs
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mpa_cape, aes(fill = CUR_NME), color = "black") +  
  scale_fill_viridis_d(name = "MPA Name") +  
  ggtitle("Marine Protected Areas") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

Figure 5: Map of South African MPAs in the Cape Peninsula region, Robben Island and False Bay, MPAs are highlighted in different colours.

There are some adjacent polygons that belong to the same MPA. Below I edit the plot to not show any unwanted boundaries.

# Remove boundaries within MPAs
mpa_cape %>% group_by(CUR_NME) %>% 
  summarize() %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_sf(aes(fill = CUR_NME)) +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Marine Protected Areas")

Figure 6: Map of South African MPAs in the Cape Peninsula region, Robben Island and False Bay, unwanted boundaries are removed.

Now it is time to add my species occurrence data from iNaturalist. I am using three species: the kelps Ecklonia maxima and Laminaria pallida, and the red alga Gelidium pristoides. I do this using the rinat() package.

# Call species occurrence data from iNaturalist

# Ecklonia maxima
em <- get_inat_obs(taxon_name = "Ecklonia maxima",
                   bounds = c(-34.6, 18.0, -33.7, 19.2),
                   maxresults = 1000)

When we have a look at the numbers in column n(), this proves to be correct. It is difficult to see where the few records within the Betty’s Bay (BB) MPA and Robben Island (RI) MPA are on the map. I am therefore locating and then labeling observations in these two.

# Find BB MPA localities
bb <- algae_data %>% filter(CUR_NME %in% c("Betty's Bay Marine Protected Area")) 

# Find RI MPA localities
ri <- algae_data %>% filter(CUR_NME %in% c("Robben Island Marine Protected Area"))  

# Label Betty's Bay (BB) MPA and Robben Island (RI) MPA 
ggplot() + 
  annotation_map_tile(type = "osm", progress = "none") + 
  geom_sf(data = algae_data, aes(col = CUR_NME)) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = pal) +
  labs(color = "Marine Protected Areas") +  # Rename the legend title here
  geom_sf_label(data = bb %>% filter(CUR_NME == "Betty's Bay Marine Protected Area"), aes(label = "BB")) +
  geom_sf_label(data = ri %>% filter(CUR_NME == "Robben Island Marine Protected Area"), aes(label = "RI")) +
  theme_minimal()

Figure 12: Map of three seaweed species occurrences within existing South African Marine Protected Areas, records from Betty’s Bay and Robben Island MPAs are labelled.

The analysis of the distribution of the three agar-producing seaweed species reveals that they all occur within established Marine Protected Areas in the study region. Therefore, the creation of new MPAs or the expansion of existing ones does not seem to be necessary.
